<h1>Marseille Month note</h1>

<ul>
<li><p><a href="pdf/Hochschild homology for red padic grp.pdf">[Hochschild homology of reductive p-adic groups note]</a>, 2025.3.</p>
<p>This is the lecture talk given by <a href="https://www.math.ru.nl/~solleveld/">Maarten Solleveld</a> from Radboud Universiteit Nijmegen.
<p>The goal of this mini-course is to explain a description of the Hochschild homology of the Hecke algebra of a reductive p-adic group, in spectral terms related to the Bernstein center.</p>
<p>Lecture 1: Introduction to Hochschild homology and twisted crossed product algebras.
<p>Lecture 2: Representation theory and Hochschild homology of graded Hecke algebras.
<p>Lecture 3: Hochschild homology of algebras associated to p-adic groups.
<p>Details can be found in the series of papers on the topics 'Hecke algebras of p-adic groups' and 'Homology of Hecke algebras' parts at his homepage. Tbh I need more time to understand how this works. Update: he just uploaded his note <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.17260">Group algebras of reductive p-adic groups, their representations and their noncommutative geometry</a>.

<p> In p-adic day of Tempered representations and C* algebra, he gave a talk on <a href="pdf/Top K theory of reductive p adic group.pdf">[Topological K-Theory of reductive p-adic groups]</a>,
which described how the K-theory can be computed from the space of irreducible tempered representations. The final description is closely related to conjectures by Aubert-Baum-Plymen-Solleveld.
</li>
</ul>


